'''Abel Resino Gonz<U+00E1>lez''' (born [[February 2]], [[1960]] in [[Velada]], [[Toledo (province)|Toledo]]) is a Spanish [[football (soccer)|football]] [[Coach (sport)|manager]] and former player. Abel has played for CD Toledo, CD Ciempozuelos and Club Atl<U+00E9>tico de Madrid, as well as for the Spanish national team as a goalkeeper. In 2005, he started coaching the [[Segunda Divisi<U+00F3>n]] team Ciudad de Murcia, where he stayed a year and almost gained promotion. The club actually promoted was [[Levante UD]], the team he coached replacing [[Juan Ram<U+00F3>n L<U+00F3>pez Caro]] since January 2007 until he was replaced by [[Gianni De Biasi]]. 

As a player he held the record for the longest [[Clean sheet|shut-out]] in the world at 1,275 minutes. He played for [[Atletico Madrid]] while achieving this record and was finally beaten by [[Luis Enrique Mart<U+00ED>nez Garc<U+00ED>a|Luis Enrique]] of [[Sporting de Gij<U+00F3>n|Sporting Gijon]] on [[19 March]][[1991]].<ref>{{cite web | title=Quirky Facts | work=Goalkeepersaredifferent.com | url=http://www.goalkeepersaredifferent.com/keeper/factframe.htm | accessdate=June 20 | accessyear=2007 }}</ref>

==Coaching philosophy and style==
Abel is regarded as an offensive manager, playing with the defensive line high up the field. This is sometimes seen as a risky style of playing.

==Playing honours==
*Atl<U+00E9>tico de Madrid:
:[[Copa del Rey]] 1991, 1992
:[[Ricardo Zamora Trophy]] 1990-1991

